<subSubSection pageId="792" pageNumber="793" type="reference_group">
<paragraph pageId="792" pageNumber="793">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chaudoir" authorityYear="1870" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Phloeoxena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="792" pageNumber="793" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Phloeoxena</taxonomicName>
Chaudoir, 1870a: 145. Type species: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chaudoir" authorityYear="1870" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Phloeoxena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="792" pageNumber="793" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="picta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="792" pageNumber="793">Phloeoxena picta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Chaudoir, 1870 designated by Ball (1975: 178). Etymology. From the Greek 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="792" pageNumber="793">phloios</emphasis>
(bark) and 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="792" pageNumber="793">xenos</emphasis>
(stranger, guest) [feminine].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="792" pageNumber="793" type="diversity">
<paragraph pageId="792" pageNumber="793">Diversity.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="792" pageNumber="793">
Thirty-four species in the temperate, subtropical, and tropical areas of the Nearctic (one eastern species) and Neotropical (34 species) Regions. These species are arrayed in five subgenera: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ball" authorityYear="1975" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Oenaphelox" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="792" pageNumber="793" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="792" pageNumber="793">Oenaphelox</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Ball (nine species), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ball" authorityYear="1975" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Tacana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="792" pageNumber="793" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="792" pageNumber="793">Tacana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Ball (one species), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chaudoir" authorityYear="1870" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Phloeoxena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="792" pageNumber="793" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="792" pageNumber="793">Phloeoxena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
s.str. (15 species), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shpeley &amp; Ball" authorityYear="2000" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Oxephloena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="792" pageNumber="793" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="792" pageNumber="793">Oxephloena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Shpeley and Ball (one species), and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1883" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Ochropisus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="792" pageNumber="793" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="792" pageNumber="793">Ochropisus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Bates (eight species).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
